Though Darkness my home, <br>
The Light is my guide, <br>
and the ability to use them both is my Salvation. <br>
The rear guard, tired and unaware, my first target, the Dragoons Blade I carry, <br>
stolen off Ambassador Dvinn, slides from its sheathe, the murky black poison drips from it. I strike, one swift motion catching it in the neck, through the voice box, <br>
not a sound, not a whisper, the remaining Orcs travel forward unawares that their friend is convulsing and dying under this beautiful moon. The time has come, dark shadows await me. <br>
My party awaits action. I pull from behind my back, a small throwing disk, and with one swift motion, it embeds itself into the arm of the largest Orc. Fight or flight, <br>
I choose flight. I'm not that stupid. <br>
I run towards the group, the roar of the Orcs is the only warning they need. <br>
The two paladins, and the Battle maiden from Qeynos, stand ready; our cleric gets our healing poultices ready, she knows, I'm thankful she's here. <br>
I run towards the meat shields as I so affectionately have dubbed them, leap in the air, and somersault behind them to the safety of the darkness. My Initial task is complete, its time for my secondary duty, protection of my cleric. Though as stupid as the orcs are, they have the uncanny ability to realize that without a cleric a group of adventurers is dead. She knows i am there. She's counting on it. She heals the paladins and our Battle Maiden, the Orcs engage her. <br>
My turn Without a sound I slip my magical Dagger of Dropping in-between he shoulder blades of the lead Orc, he bellows, and turns to find my grinning darkened face beaming a huge smile. He frenzies, his blades whirling on my like a devil. My dual daggers, parry, I dodge, I wont be able to do this long. I parry again, I am very lucky, He smashes his longsword into my ribs, and I smile even brighter. I learned many lessons while <br>
traveling alone through the commons, and this is one lesson I intend to teach this orc. No matter how much you think it hurts, it can always hurt worse. He smashed into me catching my nose with the pommel of his sword, he Kicks me tossing me to the ground. He swings his heavy sword in my direction, I can barely move out of the way, as it clangs into the ground causing sparks, the paladins and battle maiden fighting their own battle haven't seen me yet, this Orc is mad, and he's focused it all on me. I roll to the left and Kip-up, to my feet, narrowly missing contact with his blade again. He swings low for my feet; I somersault back, now i am a tad angry, He just cut my brand new tunic! <br>
He swings, as I step in catching me in the shoulder. Now the pain begins. <br>
The combat around me seems to come to a stop, I can feel the haze of adrenaline rush through me, there is no fatigue there is no blood, there is only my blades and I. The Orcs movements seem slow. The world compresses itself into a tiny ball in my hands, the void encompasses me, I dodge, he swings again, and I begin the spiral of death. His large cumbersome body doesn't spin like mine does. He bellows out in rage. He feels his doom, so do I. <br>
He swings again; I parry and strike catching him under the underarm, a mass of blood pours from the wound. He strike again, this time Aiming for my legs, <br>
<br>
He's too slow my Dragoons dirk finds the soft fleshy part in his neck under the chin, the point finding daylight through the top of his head. His heavy weight falls on top of me. I catch him but I am weakened, and in pain again, I fall into blackness, I fall homewards. <br>
<br>
The last thing I remember as I lay there bleeding from my various wounds is how <br>
beautiful the moon is tonight. <br>
<br>
<br>
Udalia <br>
17th rank Rogue<br>
&quot;Hunted in Neriak&quot;<br>
